            <div type="translation">
                <p>“(This epitaph is of) Lucius Furius Rufus, son of Lucius, from the Collina tribe; Furia Euphrosyne, freedwoman of Lucius; Furia Bassa, daughter of illegitimate birth; Lucius Furius Felix, freedman of Lucius.</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Line 1: letters are visibly larger than rest of lines; line 2: final S in Euphrosynes seems slightly smaller than rest of characters in line, and is carved shallower than first S in Euphrosynes, perhaps to fit it into campus. I longae in lines 1 (Furi and Rufi) and 4 (Furi). Through photograph, thin guidelines are visible below and above letters in each line, and possibly on right and left sides of lines. Guideline also visible near bottom of campus, however significant space between last line and bottom guideline. Triangular marks of punctuation can be seen between words, but not at the ends of lines.</p>
                <p>The identity of Lucius Furius Rufus is not known, however, it could be discerned that he is probably freeborn based on the cognomen Rufus, which was an old and respected cognomen among Roman nobility and is very rare among slaves. Identifying L. Furius Rufus with the nobility is further solidified by his identification of being from the Collina tribe, which was acknowledged as “superior” (along with Palatina) to the other two urban tribes, and includes senators, knights, and other respectable men. Furia Euphrosyne’s identity cannot be discerned beyond being of Greek origin and having been freed, probably by the named Lucius Furius Rufus. Perhaps the placement of her name right after L. Furius Rufus and before the daughter suggests some relationship between freedwoman and master. Furia Bassa is identified as an illegitimate daughter (possibly) of L. Furius Rufus, rather than the daughter of a Spurius, due to her gentilicium also being from the gens Furii. It should also be noted that, while illegitimate children were often assigned to the Collina tribe, L. Furius Rufus’s identification with the Collina tribe might simply be a coincidence and not connected to Furia Bassa’s illegitimacy. The cognomen Bassa, not of Latin origin, is not specific to a region. L. Furius Felix holds a cognomen frequently found among slaves and freedmen, and commonly found in general.</p>
                <p>Transcription from photo.</p>
            </div>
            

